SIMPLE: soothe
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Soothe
<hw>Soothe</hw> <pr>(s⟦oomac⟧⟦th⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Soothed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Soothing</conjf>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[Originally, to assent to as true; OE. <ets>so⟦edh⟧ien</ets> to
verify, AS. <ets>ges⟦omac⟧⟦edh⟧ian</ets> to prove the truth of, to bear
witness. See <er>Sooth</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
assent to as true.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Testament of
Love.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To assent to; to comply with; to gratify; to humor
by compliance; to please with blandishments or soft words; to
flatter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Good, my lord, <qex>soothe</qex> him, let him take the fellow.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I've tried the force of every reason on him,⟦br⟧
<qex>Soothed</qex> and caressed, been angry, <qex>soothed</qex>
again.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To assuage; to mollify; to calm; to comfort; <as>as,
to <ex>soothe</ex> a crying child; to <ex>soothe</ex> one's
sorrows</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Music hath charms to <qex>soothe</qex> the savage breast,⟦br⟧
To soften rocks, or bend a knotted oak.</q>
<rj><qau>Congreve.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though the sound of Fame⟦br⟧
May for a moment <qex>soothe</qex>, it can not slake⟦br⟧
The fever of vain longing.</q> <rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To soften; assuage; allay; compose; mollify;
tranquilize; pacify; mitigate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Soother</ent>⟦br⟧
